# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chief-zimmer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The **1884 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1884.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American Association's regular seasons ended on October 15, with the Providence Grays and New York Metropolitans as the NL and AA pennant winners, respectively.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The newly founded Union Association regular season ended on October 19, with the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the first World's Championship Series (the first inter-league championship game of its kind in the Major Leagues) on October 23 and ended with Game 3 on October 25, in what was a best-of-five-playoff.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Grays swept the Metropolitans in three games, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1884 season, in September 1883, the Union Association was formed, in direct contravention to the reserve rule (that a ballplayer could be reserved by a team) of the 1883 National Agreement (a.k.a.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Tripartite Agreement) signed between the National League, American Association, and minor league Northwestern League.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] In response to formation of the UA, the AA expanded their league from an eight teams to twelve teams to undermine the weak footing the UA had, as UA teams were mostly in cities that already had established AA and NL teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The latter played their last game on August 2, and were replaced by the minor league Eastern League's Richmond Virginians to finish Washington's schedule.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association was largely unstable throughout its only year in existence (though confidence in the league remained high), as three of its founding teams would not make it to the end of the season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Altoona Mountain Citys folded on May 31, and were replaced by the Kansas City Cowboys on June 7.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Keystones folded on August 7, and were replaced by the Eastern League's Wilmington Quicksteps.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Browns relocated to Pittsburgh as the Pittsburgh Stogies following their August 21 game.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Quicksteps would fold on September 15, while the Stogies would fold just three days later.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] On September 27, the Milwaukee Brewers and St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Paul Saints) were recruited from the Northwestern League to finish the Philadelphia / Wilmington and Chicago/Pittsburgh schedules, respectively.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 season featured the second African American player in the major leagues (following William Edward White five years prior), debuting May 1 and playing 42 games for the Toledo Blue Stockings of the American Association.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] During his tenure, he faced abuse from other players (including teammates), fans, and the press, and even threats of being mobbed by 75 men before a road trip to Richmond, Virginia, before being released due to injury on September 29, prior to the road trip.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] His brother Weldy Walker played on the Toledo Blue Stockings for five games between July and August, becoming the third African American in the major leagues.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 schedule consisted of 110 games for all teams in the American Association, which had twelve active teams, and 112 games for all teams in the National League and Union Association, each of which had eight active teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 10 games against the other eleven teams in their league, and each of NL & UA teams were scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League increased its total games per team from 98 to 112, 14 games to 16 games per seven opponents.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The new Union Association copied this format.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the American Association, expanding from eight to twelve teams, changed from the 98-game format to the 110-game format.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would continue to use their 112-game format through the following season, while the American Association would copy the NL format.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Union Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while American Association and National League Opening Days took place on May 1, featuring all twelve and all eight teams, respectively.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 19 featuring four teams, while the American Association and National League would see their final day of the regular season on October 15 featuring all twelve teams and four teams, respectively.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 World's Championship Series took place between October 23 and October 25.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four teams played in four neutral or alternate sites in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] 35 tie games (19 in AA, 10 in NL, 6 in UA), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four of these teams folded, one of which relocated cities prior to folding.
[src:chief-zimmer/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers hosted 11 Sunday games at the Bruce Grounds north of Indianapolis city limits in Center Township on May 18, 25, June 22, 29, July 6, 13, 20, August 3, 10, 31, and September 21.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The **1886 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1886.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago White Stockings and the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the third World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 6 on October 23, in what was a best-of-seven-playoff.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Browns defeated the White Stockings, four games to two, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Buffalo Bisons transfer into the minor league International League and Providence Grays fold.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The two open spots are filled by the newly enfranchised Kansas City Cowboys and Washington Nationals.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams, while each NL team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other seven teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were newly-implementation for the 1886 season, each replacing the 112-game, 16 games against the other seven teams format that both leagues had from 1884 and 1885.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format in 1888, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 29, also featuring six teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 23.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Brooklyn Grays of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] 28 tie games (13 in AA, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Grays of the American Association begin hosting Sunday games, playing 14 games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York on May 2, 16, 23, 30, June 6, 13, 20, July 18, 25, August 1, 22, 29, September 12 and 19.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The **1887 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1887.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 10, with the Detroit Wolverines and the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Colonels set a Major League record which still stands for the most base on balls for a team in a game, with 19 against the Cleveland Blues on 21 September.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Kansas City Cowboys folded, and saw them replaced by the American Association's Pittsburgh Alleghenys.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In place of the Alleghenys leaving the AA for the NL, the Cleveland Blues were enfranchised.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons relocated to Indianapolis, Indiana as the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] On July 14, Chicago was to play an exhibition game against the Eastern League Newark team, who were set to play black players Moses Fleetwood Walker (who formerly played in the majors in 1884 three years prior) and George Stovey (who the New York Giants had their eyes on signing).
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] With threats from Chicago to not play against Newark if Walker and Stovey played, they were substituted for the game.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Between Chicago's financial threats to not play against teams with people of color and other minor league teams creating petitions to force teams to release players of color, Organized Baseball effectively set up the baseball color line.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The color line would remain firm for 60 years until the Brooklyn Dodgers called up Jackie Robinson in 1947, breaking the color line.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The process of integration would then last for another 12 years until 1959, when the last major league team, the Boston Red Sox integrated by calling up Pumpsie Green.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were continued from their implementation the previous season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format the following season, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 16 featuring all eight teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 27, featuring four teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 10 with four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 8, featuring all eight teams.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 World's Championship Series took place between October 10 and October 26.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 season saw many radical changes which affected the game, as well as unity on rules by the American Association and National League.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams played in two neutral site games in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (14 in AA, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Historical statistics for the season were later revised, such that "Bases on balls shall always be treated as neither a time at bat nor a hit for the batter." This results in ambiguity for some players' season and career hits totals, notably with Cap Anson.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] Anson was credited with a .421 average and the National League batting title in 1887; however, the recalculation of averages with walks excluded lowered his average to .347 and retroactively gave the batting title to Sam Thompson.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The 1887 batting average and hits are included below, using contemporary data on Baseball Reference.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues join the American Association and play at National League Park in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:chief-zimmer/1887-major-league-baseball-season] The first structure of the South End Grounds, home of the Boston Beaneaters, would see its last game on September 10, seeing a completely new structure built over the following offseason.
[src:chief-zimmer/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1892 Cleveland Spiders**, led by star pitcher Cy Young, finished with a 93–56 overall record, second-best in the National League.
[src:chief-zimmer/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] In the first split season in Major League Baseball history, the Spiders finished in fifth place during the first half of the season, and in first place during the second half.
[src:chief-zimmer/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season, they played against the first-half champions, the Boston Beaneaters, in the "World's Championship Series", which the Spiders lost, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:chief-zimmer/1895-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1895 Cleveland Spiders** finished with an 84–46 record and a second-place finish in the National League.
[src:chief-zimmer/1895-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season they played the first-place Baltimore Orioles in the Temple Cup series, defeating them 4 games to 1.
[src:chief-zimmer/1895-temple-cup] The **1895 Temple Cup** was an end-of-the-year best-of-seven playoff between the National League champion Baltimore Orioles and runner-up Cleveland Spiders.
[src:chief-zimmer/1895-temple-cup] The series began on October 2 and ended on October 8 with the Spiders winning in five games.
[src:chief-zimmer/1895-temple-cup] In this second iteration of the Temple Cup, the NL pennant winning Baltimore Orioles, who were also in their second Temple Cup, once again lost to the NL runner-up team.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1899 Cleveland Spiders season** was the team's 13th and final season in Major League Baseball (MLB), and their 11th season in the National League (NL).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders' team owners, the Robison family, also owned the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] To strengthen the Perfectos, they transferred the Spiders' best players to St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis before the season, leaving Cleveland with a severely depleted roster.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As the Spiders played abysmally and continued to lose that season, fans stopped attending their home games, and other teams refused to travel to Cleveland to play road games against the Spiders.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This resulted in the Spiders being forced to play most of their games on the road.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL, with a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This remains the worst single-season record for an MLB team in terms of both losses and of winning percentage (.130).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team allowed 1,252 runs while only scoring 529, a run differential of −723 for the season, the worst in MLB history.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders pitchers hit 109 batters, setting an MLB single-season record that would stand for 123 years until the 2022 Cincinnati Reds hit 110 batters.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, the owners of the Spiders, brothers Frank and Stanley Robison, bought the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Browns baseball club from Chris von der Ahe, renaming it the Perfectos.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they continued to retain ownership of the Cleveland club, an obvious conflict of interest that was later prohibited by MLB.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons decided that a good team in St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis would draw more fans, so they transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, as well as manager Patsy Tebeau to St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Most of the players Cleveland received were non-entities.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Jack Clements (known to history as one of MLB's few left-handed throwing catchers) and Joe Quinn were at the end of successful careers, and player-manager Lave Cross was traded back to St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis after the Spiders got off to an 8–30 start.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also transferred numerous home games to the road—including the original Opening Day game to St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders did not play their first home game until May 1.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early April, the Spiders started training in Terre Haute, Indiana.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Because of the cold weather, the team had to practice inside a gymnasium.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] With a decimated roster, it was apparent almost from the start that the Spiders would make a wretched showing.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After a poor start on the road, the Spiders played a home-opening doubleheader on May 1 in front of 100 fans.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They split the two games, moving up to 11th place.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] However, they were back in last before long.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 2, the Spiders led the Brooklyn Superbas, 10–0, in the sixth inning, but they blew the lead and ended up losing, 11–10.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On June 11, the Spiders lost to the Cincinnati Reds, 10–1, behind Frank Bates' poor pitching.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] It was the Spiders' 11th straight loss on that road trip.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The following day, the Spiders returned home and lost to the Pittsburgh Pirates in front of 58 fans.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team kept losing games, and losses came more and more frequently as the season went on.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 16, with Bates pitching, the Spiders lost to the Superbas, 13–2.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] This led to criticism from the *Cleveland Plain Dealer*.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On August 18, the first-place Superbas completed their sweep of the Spiders, outscoring them, 43–8, in four games.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders notched their 100th loss of the season on August 31, falling to the Superbas, 9–3.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Two days later, the Spiders played a local amateur team in Johnstown, Pennsylvania, and lost, 7–5.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On September 12, the Spiders lost both games of a doubleheader to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] At that point, they were 19–114 and had broken the MLB single-season record for losses, which had been 113.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] On October 15, the Spiders ended their season by losing both games of a doubleheader to the Cincinnati Reds, by scores of 16–1 and 19–3.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After losing 40 of their last 41 games, they had a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their record is still the worst in Major League Baseball history.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They trailed the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas by 84 games, and finished 35 games behind the 11th place Washington Senators.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] For comparison, this would project to 21–141 under the current schedule, and Pythagorean expectation based on the Spiders' results and the current 162-game schedule would translate to a record of 25–137.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20 against the Phillies and May 21 against the Colonels.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] They also accumulated the second-longest losing streak in league history, at 24 games from August 26 to September 16, trailing only the 26-game losing streak set by the 1889 Louisville Colonels.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were winless against two teams: Brooklyn and Cincinnati.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The pitching staff allowed a record 1,252 runs in 154 games.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders batters combined to hit 12 home runs, matching former Spiders star Bobby Wallace, who hit 12 home runs for St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The 1899 Spiders did lead the league in one statistic—games played.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Cleveland was the only team in the league to finish all of its games in the then-154 game schedule of the 1899 season, a rather unusual occurrence in that era.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Due to poor attendance, the Spiders played 112 road games, as a result of 35 of their planned home games being moved.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] In early 1899, team Robison Brothers publicly announced their intention to run the Spiders "as a sideshow", and fans took them at their word: after the first 16 home games, Cleveland's total attendance was 3,179, for a trifling average of 199 people per game.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, other NL teams refused to travel to Cleveland's League Park, since their cut of the ticket revenue would not even come close to covering their travel and hotel expenses.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] As a result, the Spiders only played 26 more home games for the rest of the season, including only eight after July 1.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Their records of 112 road games and 101 road losses will never be threatened: it is currently unbreakable under MLB's current scheduling practices, where a team plays a maximum of 81 road games.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The only time it was even considered approachable was the aforementioned 1994 Mariners, but the strike of that season ended the possibility of them breaking the record, and no team has played more than 81 road games since then (not counting 1 or 3 game tiebreaker playoff games).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] A mere 6,088 fans paid for Spiders home games in 1899, an average of 145 people per game.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis drew 373,909 fans for their home season, including 15,000 for one game (their home opener against the Spiders).
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The dismal 1899 season was the end for the Spiders, and for National League baseball in Cleveland.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders were disbanded, along with the original Baltimore Orioles, the Louisville Colonels (Louisville, nor the entire state of Kentucky, has had another professional sports team since), and the original Washington Senators, as the National League contracted from 12 teams to 8.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The departure of baseball from Cleveland left an opening for the upstart American League, which opened for business in 1901 as a second major league and included among its charter members a new team, the Cleveland Blues.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Blues still exist today as the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Currently, the 2024 Chicago White Sox (121) has the post-1900 AL and MLB records for most losses in a season.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] After the Spiders folded, a National League team would not play in Cleveland again until the Brooklyn Robins visited the then-Cleveland Indians in the 1920 World Series.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis, the Perfectos were renamed the St.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] Louis Cardinals in 1900, which they are still called today.
[src:chief-zimmer/1899-cleveland-spiders-season] The Robisons purchasing of the Browns/Perfectos/Cardinals essentially began a turnaround for the organization, as they eventually became one of the most recognizable teams in baseball in the 20th century, appearing in 15 World Series and winning 9.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer is regarded by some as "the finest defensive catcher of his day." He set major-league catching records for assists (188 in 1890), double plays (16 in 1895), runners caught stealing (183 in 1893), games at catcher (125 in 1890), and career fielding percentage (.943 as of 1896).
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] As one of the game's first every-day catchers, *The Sporting News* in 1949 called Zimmer "baseball's original 'iron man'." Offensively, Zimmer had a career batting average of .269, but hit above .300 four times, including a career-high .340 batting average in 1895.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was also the first president of the Players' Protective Association and a successful entrepreneur during his playing days, including operation of a wholesale and retail cigar business that he promoted while on the road.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] His most famous business venture, however, was "Zimmer's Baseball Game", a mechanical baseball parlor game that he invented in 1891 and became popular in the early to middle 1890s.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was born in Marietta, Ohio, in 1860.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] As a young man, he worked as an apprentice in a cabinetmaker's shop.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He began his professional baseball career at age 23 in 1884 playing in the Ohio State League for teams from Ironton and Portsmouth, Ohio.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He appeared in eight games in the Major Leagues for the Detroit Wolverines in 1884.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] After being released by the Tigers, Zimmer did not play professional baseball in 1885.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He played for Poughkeepsie of the Hudson River League in 1886, compiling a .409 batting average, and for the Rochester Maroons of the International Association in 1887, batting .331.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer acquired the nickname "Chief" during the 1886 season while playing as the captain of the Poughkeepsie team.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was not of American Indian descent and explained the genesis for the nickname as follows: "Since we were fleet of foot, we were called the Indians.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer is regarded by some as "the finest defensive catcher of his day." Baseball historian Bill James picked Zimmer as the catcher both for his 1890s Gold Glove team and his 1890s All-Star team, and as the 62nd best catcher of all time.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] From 1889 to 1900, Zimmer was regularly among his league's leaders in putouts, assists, double plays, fielding percentage and games played at catcher.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer is also credited with being the first catcher, in 1887, to play from a squatting position directly behind the plate on every play.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In prior years, catchers had played further behind the plate often standing, particularly with runners on base.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During Zimmer's time, catchers' gloves had not evolved and did not provide the protection of a modern catcher's mitt.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Interviewed in 1949, Zimmer indicated that the catcher's glove in the 1890s was similar to an outfielders glove, and he would occasionally pad it with a piece of beefsteak to further protect his hands from injury.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1892, when asked how he kept his hands healthy so as to be able to catch in so many games, Zimmer also said he received regular hand massages: "He replied that he made it a practice to visit a massage establishment whenever his hands gave him the slightest cause for trouble.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] After brief stints with the Detroit Wolverines (eight games in 1884) and New York Metropolitans (six games in 1886), Zimmer joined the Cleveland Blues in 1887.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He remained in Cleveland for 13 seasons from 1887 through 1899.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] From 1890 to 1898, Zimmer was Cy Young's catcher during Young's formative and most dominant years as a pitcher, and the two remained close friends for 60 years.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1890, Cleveland finished in seventh place with a 44–88 record; Young, in his rookie season, was 9–7.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] From the low point in 1890, Zimmer, the club and Young all improved remarkably.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1891, Zimmer had a career-high 69 RBIs with a 1.6 Wins Above Replacement (WAR) rating.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He caught 116 games in 1891, but underwent knee surgery after the season was over.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The following year, in 1892, Zimmer compiled a career-high 3.2 WAR rating and led the 1892 Cleveland Spiders to a franchise best record of 93–56 (.624), good for second place in the National League.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The 1892 season was also a breakout year for Young who compiled a 36–12 record with a 1.93 earned run average (ERA).
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1893, the distance between the pitcher and home plate was extended by nine feet, resulting in a dramatic increase in batting averages.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The rule change helped Zimmer statistically, as he compiled a .308 batting average, the first of four .300 seasons.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] However, Zimmer bemoaned the rule change's effect on pitchers: "They are making the pitcher a mere automaton.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] By and by they will make him stand on a cake of ice and pitch.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Say what you will, the pitcher is the central figure in the game.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] People pay their money to see base ball, and the more scientific it is the better.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In July 1893, he suffered a broken shoulder bone and was able to play only 56 games behind the plate.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The injury was sustained in a collision with Tommy Tucker.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Cleveland newspapers protested and claimed that Tucker was a player with a reputation as a habitual dirty player who had acted intentionally to injure Zimmer.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1894, Zimmer became one of the first players to get six hits in a single game, doing so off Win Mercer.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was the batting hero of the 1895 Temple Cup, hitting a two-run home run to win the decisive game.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In late March 1896, Zimmer left the Spiders' spring training camp in a contract dispute, and one week later reportedly signed a contract providing for him to be paid the maximum salary of $2,400 plus an $800 signing bonus.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The *Sporting Life* reported: "If there is one player whose services Mr.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Robison(Cleveland owner Frank Robison) cannot afford to lose, it is Charley Zimmer.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In spring, summer and fall or any old time at all chief is in condition." On September 24, 1896, two masked men armed with revolvers woke Zimmer and his wife at their home at 43 Steinway Street in Cleveland.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The intruders robbed Zimmer of his $60 gold watch and $20 in cash.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1897, at age 36, Zimmer continued to impress.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He compiled a .316 batting average and a 1.9 WAR rating while helping Young win 20 games for the seventh consecutive season.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] After the 1898 season, Young left the Spiders, and Zimmer, at age 38, was released by the team in early June 1899, despite having compiled a .342 batting average in 20 games.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Without Young or Zimmer, the 1899 Cleveland Spiders compiled a 20-134 (.130) record—the worst record in Major League history.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In June 1899, Zimmer was signed as a free agent by the Louisville Colonels.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He appeared in 75 games for Louisville in 1899, compiling a .298 batting average.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] For the second time in his career, Zimmer was responsible for mentoring a future Hall of Fame pitcher in his rookie season.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] At Louisville, the rookie pitcher was Rube Waddell.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In December 1899, Zimmer was part of a blockbuster trade with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In addition to Zimmer, the Colonels sent three future Hall of Famers (Waddell, Honus Wagner and Fred Clarke) to the Pirates in exchange for Jack Chesbro, three other players, and $25,000.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During the 1900 season, Zimmer was the oldest player in the Major Leagues at age 39.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Aside from a .295 batting average, Zimmer caught 82 games, led the National League with 318 putouts and totaled 89 runners caught stealing.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Moreover, under Zimmer's tutelage, Rube Waddell in his first season as a regular starter, led the National League with a 2.37 ERA.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The following year, Zimmer remained the oldest player in the Major Leagues at age 40.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He caught 69 games for the 1901 Pirates team that won the National League pennant with a 90–49 record.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During the 1901 season, Zimmer caught for his third Hall of Fame pitcher, Jack Chesbro.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1902, at age 41, Zimmer caught 41 games, compiled a .268 batting average, and maintained a respectable 1.1 WAR rating.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The Pirates won the pennant for the second consecutive year with a 103–36 record.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In early 1903, the Philadelphia Phillies were sold, and the new owners, with the assistance of Pittsburgh owner Barney Dreyfuss, persuaded Zimmer to become the Phillies' manager.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer agreed and also appeared in 35 games as the team's catcher.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In May 1903, the *Sporting Life* newspaper wrote that Zimmer was still a solid performer behind the plate: "The Phillies' pitchers do their best work and the team is strongest when the veteran Zimmer is in the game.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] A wink should be as good as a kick, Chief." Zimmer appeared in his final Major League game as a player at age 42 on September 27, 1903.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In his role as manager, Zimmer took over a team that had finished in seventh place in 1902.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] By the first of June 1903, the Phillies were struggling with an 11–26 record.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] However, with a seventh-place finish, the 1903 season was Zimmer's only one as a Major League manager.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In fairness to Zimmer, the Phillies simply lacked the talent to compete with the best teams in the National League, had finished in seventh place in 1902 under Bill Shettsline, and dropped to eighth place in 1904 under Hugh Duffy.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During his baseball career, Zimmer was among the highest paid players in the game.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He invested his money wisely and was alert for investment opportunities.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] By 1900, his business interests included "upward of $35,000 invested in the grocery business and real estate in Cleveland." He also owned a restaurant in Cleveland and used his wood-working skills to make furniture in the off-season.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The business opportunity that drew the most attention was "Zimmer's Base Ball Game", a mechanical baseball table game developed by Zimmer in 1891.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The game featured a painted ball field with children peeking over the one-and-a-half inch outfield wall as well as lithographed images of Zimmer and 18 other players, including 11 Hall of Famers.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In January 1892, Zimmer was offered "a big amount of money" for his interest in the game, and it was estimated "by judicious business management" that 100,000 copies of the game could be sold.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In October 1892, Zimmer stated that he expected to sell "a great many of his parlor baseball inventions" over the winter and noted that one New York firm had purchased 600 from him.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Two years later, he reported that he had a large number of orders for the game and that he had made over $4,000 from the game over the past three years.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Unlike many baseball players of his era, Zimmer used neither liquor nor tobacco.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Despite his personal aversion to tobacco, Zimmer in the 1890s was successful in operating a wholesale and retail cigar business in Cleveland.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In 1898, as he traveled with the Cleveland team, he carried a valise with samples of the cigars that he sold.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During the summer of 1900, the Players' Protective Association, predecessor to the Major League Baseball Players Association, was formed to represent the interest of professional baseball players.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was elected as the organization's first president with Hughie Jennings secretary.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During Zimmer's tenure as president, the organization successfully negotiated for a new rule providing that a player could not be traded or sold without his consent.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The *Sporting Life* later wrote that Zimmer was the "only man who ever showed marked ability" as president of the Association.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The consent rule that Zimmer secured was later rescinded, and the Association's reputation declined.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During the 1904 and 1905 seasons, Zimmer worked as an umpire: first in the National League where he umpired 151 games in 1904, and then in the Eastern League (a minor league that later became the International League) in 1905.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The following year, he staged a comeback as a player at age 45.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] In February 1906, he was hired as the player/manager for the Little Rock Travelers in the Southern Association.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Even at age 45, Zimmer still displayed superior arm strength.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] After a Little Rock victory in May 1906, the *Sporting Life* newspaper reported: "Little Rock showed wonderful improvement and defeated Birmingham in a well-played game.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] The feature was the throwing of Zimmer to second." He appeared in 41 games as a player for Little Rock.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] His Little Rock team finished in last place with a 40–98 record.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was among a number of Cleveland players who played in an Old-Timers' Day in July 1921; Zimmer, aged 60, caught for his former battery-mate Cy Young, aged 55.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] Zimmer was married and had three daughters.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] During his playing career, he made furniture as a hobby during the off-season and filled his home in Cleveland with his handiwork.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] After retiring from baseball, Zimmer lived in Cleveland for the remainder of his life.
[src:chief-zimmer/chief-zimmer] He was buried at Crown Hill Cemetery in Twinsburg, Ohio.
